When I was 8 or so my parent and stepabuser moved us to Texas. Not having resources or a plan they crashed on a friend's couch (with the two kids on the floor). He was the oddball friend from work to my stepabuser, I think.

He was late 20s or early 30s, just a tall gawky man with a horse laugh with a huge fantasy poster on his bedroom door. And was infinitely kinder than he should of been. Got quietly happy when I agreed to call him uncle. 1/

He was gay or bi, never asked him, but he dated guys and was sweet on this one blond. I don't even remember his boyfriends name anymore.

Both he and his boyfriend died from AIDS.

My parent & stepabuser abandoned him outside a hospital. Left him there with me in the fucking car. They'd knew, accepted him; but somehow this was 'wrong' all of a sudden.

Gods. A lot of people don't understand what the fuck the 70s & 80s were like for people. Especially the misfits and outcasts.
2/2

After dedicating my second run to minmaxing my stats for it, I have finally gotten the best possible outcome of the mercenary tribunal without savescumming!
All checks were a full 97% likely, my stat spread was 6 on H/E Coordination, 6 on Logic, 6 on Rhetoric, 6 on Authority, 7 on Suggestion, and 3 on Reaction Speed. I had every modifier for every red check open, the FT-500 thought, every piece of T-500 armor I could get equipped, and my weapon of choice was the Villiers 9mm I got from The Pigs. (Two bullets, I only used one)
The casualties on the union side were Theo, Angus, and Glen, which is the minimum, and the casualties on the mercs' side were all three of them, which is the maximum.
Kim survived, of course.
My initial spread for the run was 4/1/4/3, so I *really* worked hard to get Suggestion and Authority, it payed off, though!

One of the reasons it took me so long to even bother questioning is just how inconsistent people look at stuff. "You can't be trans if you don't have dysphoria" and "You don't need to be dysphoric, just follow your heart" seem to be out there in equal measure, and when I *did* finally get the self-confidence to start questioning, that changed to "well no if you're not publicly displaying it, it doesn't count" and vice versa

I'm lucky enough to not particularly be dysphoric and don't really care about which pronouns get used, but there's a weirdly big set of people who seem to not even be okay with me calling myself enby because I'm still using my birth name on official documents and for mail and stuff (even though online and for consulting work I use Jess), and still very masc presenting (something that's probably not going to change any time soon). It's really tiring and confusing. Am I doing things right or not??

I'd love to hear some folks' takes on this since I feel like I'll get more reasonable opinions on here compared to Twitter or Reddit
I've tried not to say anything about horrible losses of life, but is this here not the definition of ethnic cleansing?

Hey, #neurodivergent bubble, I have a question. Do you know that situation when you know someone who shows clear symptoms of neurodivergence and you are able to feel their struggles but they don't know or just don't want to believe that they could have #ADHD or #autism or something else, and you just can't ask them to consider it?
I've had this several times. A friend of mine who I believe has AD(H)D, but he just won't talk about it; a coworker who I used to talk to a lot (before he got fired because of his instable behavior) and he was like straight from the #ADHD rule book - He was mega hesitant to give #neurodiversity a second thought. Then there was a woman in an office where I had an internship, who was so #autistic that I could tell within a few interactions. I really, really am not the kind of person who runs around diagnosing everyone around in my head!

Instead I'll buy Interrail passes now, making use of my advantageous living situation. In my home country Austria a nationwide one year subscription for all public transport is relatively cheap at 821‚Ç¨. From my nearest station the travel time to Switzerland is 8 minutes and to Germany it is 25min. I can therefore make use of Interrail not only for longer trips, but also for much of my everyday life.

This brings me to the next question: Which Interrail pass do I buy? My daily commute, albeit international, is fully covered by the Austrian Klimaticket. Therefore it is probably cheaper to go with something like 15 days in two months. But that means I that each trip is still associated with a cost, one travel day. My plan for now is to first use up the passes I have left from cancelled summer plans and then buy 3 months continuous. After that, I can use my Tr√§welling data to evaluate how many travel days I really need.

With the Deutschlandticket its a similar story: I rarely need busses, Trams or subways, so buying individual tickets is probably cheaper. But I'll have to evaluate that through Tr√§welling.

The best part about it: I finally get unrestricted access to Switzerland, which previously was way too expensive to travel in

I keep being offered work that I'm very well qualified for, but from organisations/ people that have no idea that I'm qualified for it. And...I don't like it.

Extreme example: last week I was asked to attend a 2-day conference on a niche topic. I actually wrote a whole publication on this exact topic last year. But it was ghostwritten, it's not linked to my name anywhere and the client has no idea I know ANYTHING about this topic.

Hard to explain why it makes me feel uneasy and dissatisfied. I suppose the sheer randomness of it. Knowing that there's no connection between my expertise and the work I'm getting makes me feel like I don't really have control over anything, I suppose. It's all about existing relationships and the laziness/availability bias of the people who hire me, not my hard work or skill.

We often got together for drinks at a local pub and we‚Äôd catch up on family, sports, news, and other goings on. There‚Äôd be banter, and lots of ribbing.

One day the pub had a small fireworks display planned and everyone gathered for the start. You can probably imagine where this is going.

After about 20s or so, he‚Äôd stopped laughing and smiling and stood gripping the table, staring at the floor. He winced with every firework.

Before long he‚Äôd move along the bench to beside the wall, his knees brought to his chest and his hands over his ears. He started to hyperventilate.

This was the first time this had ever happened.

Within seconds, the group stopped laughing and just switched into caregiving mode. They knew exactly what this was and how to help.

Some other bargoers had started to look and laugh, making comments to their friends. But we didn‚Äôt, there was no judgement here.

The guy had saved everyone around the table several times over.

Within a few minutes he started to come-to, but when I see Puss in Boots, this is all I see, and it‚Äôs so accurate.

What really brings a tear to my eye, is the bewilderment they captured. Losing control of one‚Äôs self.

You are a passenger in your own body and he had no idea what was happening to him. His own brain working against him.

Na ruim 10 jaar constant geklaag tegenover activisten aan te moeten horen ben ik het intussen wel echt zat, en mijn geduld hiervoor begint steeds minder te worden.

Als activist kun je het nooit goed doen - dan ben je te gewelddadig, dan ben je niet gewelddadig genoeg. Iedereen heeft er een mening over en twijfelt niet om die te verkondigen.

Er is geen enkele erkenning dat activisme ook gewoon een specialisme is zoals ieder ander, en dat mensen die het al jaren doen misschien een idee hebben wat ze doen; nee hoor, de beste stuurlui staan aan wal, en iemand die in z'n leven nog nooit een demonstratie van dichtbij gezien heeft leest je gerust de les over hoe "je zo toch echt niets gaat bereiken".

Loop je een demonstratie, dan "gaat toch niemand zich daar iets van aantrekken, en je verstoort alleen maar de orde".

Begin je een juridisch proces, dan is het "kansloos en het rechtssysteem overbelasten met onzin, doe eens echt wat".

Blokkeer je een weg, dan "val je onschuldige automobilisten lastig en creeer je gevaarlijke situaties".

Sloop je dingen, dan "ben je gewelddadig en moet je het netjes proberen op te lossen door de politiek in te gaan".

Ga je de politiek in, dan wordt je weggezet als lachertje en als publieke schietschijf gebruikt want "dit kan je toch niet serieus nemen" (zie bijvoorbeeld de reacties op BIJ1).

Ja, wat wil je godverdomme nou? Hoe denk je, precies, dat problemen opgelost gaan worden? Door wat van de zijlijn te roepen en te hopen dat de situatie op magische wijze verandert? Door te vertrouwen op de "steady march of progress" (die overigens het gevolg is van, jawel, activisme)?

Als je niet bereid bent om concreet bij te dragen aan activistische campagnes, prima, maar bemoei je er dan ook niet mee en laat het over aan de mensen die het *wel* begrijpen voorbij het niveau 'onderbuikgevoel'. Erken dat het een specialisme is dat je niet hebt.

Neem een stap terug, onthoud je van eigen commentaar of mening, en leg de focus op wat activisten zelf zeggen. Ondersteun ze op de manier waar om gevraagd wordt.

Of als je *wel* bij activisme betrokken wilt raken, ook prima - maar neem dan ook de tijd en moeite om te begrijpen waarom campagnes werken zoals ze doen, waarom activisten doen wat ze doen, en hoe dat op de lange termijn effecten kan hebben die je niet direct voor ogen hebt.
Late toevoeging: en zeker als je vaker kritiek hebt op de tactieken van activisten, dan op de dingen waartegen ze ageren, dan moet je je echt even achter de oren krabben over waar je mee bezig bent.

As an activist, whatever you do, it'll always be wrong - you're too violent, you're not violent enough. Everybody has an opinion about it, and they won't hesitate to voice it.

There is absolutely zero recognition that activism is a skill like any other, and that perhaps the people who have been doing it for years, might actually know what they're doing.

Instead, people who wouldn't recognize a protest if it hit them in the ass and certainly have never been involved in one, will lecture you about how "you won't accomplish anything this way".

You walk a protest march? "Nobody will give a shit anyway, you're just disrupting people's lives"

You go to court? "Hopeless, you're just wasting the time of the legal system"

You block a road? "You're just bothering innocent drivers, and creating dangerous situations"

You wreck shit? "You're violent, and you should go through the correct channels instead, go into politics"

You decide to go into politics? You'll be laughed out of the room, and constantly ridiculed about how "you can't possibly be expected to be taken seriously".

Well, what the fuck do you want then? How, exactly, do you think that problems are going to be solved? By yelling some shit from the sidelines, and hoping that the situation will magically change?

By relying on the "steady march of progress"? Which, by the way, is driven by activism?

If you're not willing to make a concrete contribution to activist campaigns, fine, but then *shut up*, do not meddle with them, and leave the job to the people who actually understand how activism works beyond gut feelings. Acknowledge that it is a skill, and it is not yours.

Take a step back, withhold comments and opinions, and instead amplify what activists are saying. Provide them with support in the manner that they request.

Or if you *do* want to get involved with activism, then that's also fine - but then you need to take the time and effort to understand why campaigns work how they do, why *activists* do what they do, and what the long-term effects of this might be that aren't immediately obvious to you.

That realization sits behind my series of #noir novels about the two-fisted forensic accountant #MartinHench, which started with last April's #RedTeamBlues and continues with #TheBezzle, this coming February:

https://us.macmillan.com/books/9781250865847/red-team-blues

A typical noir hero is an unlicensed cop, who goes places the cops can't go and asks questions the cops can't ask.

2/

The noir part comes at the end, when the hero is forced to admit that he's being going places the cops didn't *want* to go and asking questions the cops didn't *want* to ask. Marty Hench is a noir hero, but he's not an unlicensed cop, he's an unlicensed IRS inspector, and like other noir heroes, his capers keep resulting in his realization that the questions and places the IRS won't investigate are down to their *choice* not to investigate, not an inability to investigate.

3/

The IRS Files are a testimony to this proposition: that #LeonaHemsley wasn't wrong when she said, "Taxes are for the little people." Helmsley's crime wasn't believing that proposition - it was stating it aloud, repeatedly, to the press. The tax-avoidance strategies revealed in the IRS Files are *obviously* tax evasion, and the IRS simply let it slide.

4/

Instead, they focused their auditing firepower on working people who couldn't afford to defend themselves, looking for minor compliance errors committed by people receiving public benefits.

Or at least, that's how it *used* to be. But the Biden administration poured billions into the IRS, greenlighting 30,000 new employees whose mission would be to investigate the kinds of 0.1%ers and giant multinational corporations who'd Helmsleyed their way into tax-free fortunes.

5/

The fact that these elite monsters paid no tax was hardly a secret, and the impunity with which they functioned was a constant, corrosive force that delegitimized American society as a place where the rules only applied to everyday people and not the rich and powerful who preyed on them.

6/

The poster-child for the IRS's new anti-impunity campaign is Microsoft, who, decades ago, "sold its IP to to an 85-person factory it owned in a small Puerto Rican city," brokered a deal with the corporate friendly Puerto Rican government to pay almost no taxes, and channeled all its profits through the tiny facility:

https://www.propublica.org/article/the-irs-decided-to-get-tough-against-microsoft-microsoft-got-tougher

7/

That was in 2005. Now, the IRS has come after Microsoft for all the taxes it evaded through the gambit, demanding that the company pay it *$29 billion*. What's more, the courts are taking the IRS's side in this case, consistently ruling against Microsoft as it seeks to keep its ill-gotten billions:

https://www.propublica.org/article/irs-microsoft-audit-back-taxes-puerto-rico-billions

Now, no one expect that Microsoft is going to write a check to the IRS tomorrow.

8/

The company's made it clear that they intend to tie this up in the courts for a decade if they can, claiming, for example, that Trump's amnesty for corporate tax-cheats means the company doesn't have to give up a dime.

This gambit has worked for Microsoft before. After seven years in #antitrust hell in the 1990s, the company was eventually convicted of violating the #ShermanAct, America's bedrock competition law.

9/

But they kept the case in court until 2001, running out the clock until #GWBush was elected and let them go free. Bush had a very selective version of being "tough on crime."

But for all that Microsoft escaped being broken up, the seven years of depositions, investigations, subpoenas and negative publicity took a toll on the company.

10/

#BillGates was personally humiliated when he became the star of the first viral video, as grainy VHS tapes of his disastrous and belligerent deposition spread far and wide:

https://pluralistic.net/2020/09/12/whats-a-murder/#miros-tilde-1

If you really want to know who Bill Gates is beneath that sweater-vested savior persona, check out the antitrust deposition - it's still a banger, 25 years on:

https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2020/09/revisiting-the-spectacular-failure-that-was-the-bill-gates-deposition/

11/

In cases like these, #TheProcessIsThePunishment: Microsoft's dirty laundry was aired far and wide, its swaggering founder was brought low, and the company's conduct changed for *years* afterwards. Gates once told #KaraSwisher that Microsoft missed its chance to buy #Android because they were "distracted by the antitrust trial." But the Android acquisition came *four years* after the antitrust case ended.

12/

What Gates meant was that four years after he wriggled off the DoJ's hook, he was still so wounded and gunshy that he lacked the nerve to risk the regulatory scrutiny that such an anticompetitive merger would entail.

What's more, *other* companies got the message too. Large companies watched what happened to Microsoft and traded their reckless disregard for antitrust law for a timid respect.

13/

The effect eventually wore off, but the Microsoft antitrust case created a brief window where real competition was possible without the constant threat of being crushed by lawless monopolists. Sometimes you have to execute an admiral to encourage the others.

A decade in IRS hell will be even more painful for Microsoft than the antitrust years were.

14/

For one thing, the Puerto Rico scam was led by ex-CEO #SteveBallmer, a man possessed of so little executive function that it's a supreme irony that he was ever a corporate executive. 15/

I called out ‚ÄúGramps?‚Äù as I moved from room to room, and I saw that his keys were on the kitchen table and that his shoes were by the door, so I went to his bedroom and whispered ‚ÄúGramps?‚Äù and knocked softly, as though he was asleep.

But I think I knew, even before I opened the door. Otherwise, why would I have peeled back the covers?

14/

Why would I have reached out to touch the exposed skin of his neck, felt how cold it was? Why would I have turned him over, boneless and limp, and put my ear next to his mouth, knowing there would be no breath sounds?

I called the nonemergency number and told them my grandfather was dead, that he had died in his sleep, and then I filled the biggest glass in the kitchen with cold brew. I was going to need to stay awake for a while yet.
